A distinct rendering area of a Swing component. A component may support one or more regions. Specific component regions are defined by the typesafe enumeration in this class. 
<p> Regions are typically used as a way to identify the <code>Component</code>s and areas a particular style is to apply to. Synth's file format allows you to bind styles based on the name of a <code>Region</code>. The name is derived from the field name of the constant: </p>
<ol> 
 <li>Map all characters to lowercase. </li>
 <li>Map the first character to uppercase. </li>
 <li>Map the first character after underscores to uppercase. </li>
 <li>Remove all underscores. </li>
</ol> For example, to identify the 
<code>SPLIT_PANE</code> 
<code>Region</code> you would use 
<code>SplitPane</code>. The following shows a custom 
<code>SynthStyleFactory</code> that returns a specific style for split panes: 
<pre>    public SynthStyle getStyle(JComponent c, Region id) {
        if (id == Region.SPLIT_PANE) {
            return splitPaneStyle;
        }
        ...
    }
 </pre> The following 
<a href="doc-files/synthFileFormat.html">xml</a> accomplishes the same thing: 
<pre> &lt;style id="splitPaneStyle"&gt;
   ...
 &lt;/style&gt;
 &lt;bind style="splitPaneStyle" type="region" key="SplitPane"/&gt;
 </pre>
<p></p>
